y 1121":"18 januari 1121","1065":"1065","1087":"1087","1117":"1117","1149":"1149","1068":"1068","1112":"1112","1144":"1144","about 1112":"circa 1112","Le Monastier-sur-Gazeille, Haute-Loire, Auvergne, France":"Le Monastier-sur-Gazeille, Haute-Loire, Auvergne, Frankrijk","France":"Frankrijk","Mauguio, Hérault, Occitanie, France":"Mauguio, Hérault, Occitanie, Frankrijk","Castelnau-le-Lez, Hérault, Occitanie, France":"Castelnau-le-Lez, Hérault, Occitanie, Frankrijk"},"en":{"1091–environ 1132":"1091–about 1132","1091–1132":"1091–1132","1087–1149":"1087–1149","1112–1144":"1112–1144","1117–1190":"1117–1190","1068–1120":"1068–1120","1065–Female":"1065–Deceased","1091":"1091","1190":"1190","environ 1132":"about 1132","1132":"1132","1120":"1120","18 January 1121":"18 January 1121","1065":"1065","1087":"1087","1117":"1117","1149":"1149","1068":"1068","1112":"1112","1144":"1144","about 1112":"about 1112","Le Monastier-sur-Gazeille, Haute-Loire, Auvergne, France":"Le Monastier-sur-Gazeille, Haute-Loire, Auvergne, France","France":"France","Mauguio, Hérault, Occitanie, France":"Mauguio, Hérault, Occitanie, France","Castelnau-le-Lez, Hérault, Occitanie, France":"Castelnau-le-Lez, Hérault, Occitanie, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Bernard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>ber(n)</i> ‘bear’ + <i>hard</i> ‘hardy, brave, strong’. This was the name of three famous medieval churchmen:  St Bernard  of Menthon (  923–1008 ), founder of a hospice on each of the Alpine passes named after him; the monastic reformer  St Bernard  of Clairvaux (  1090–1153 ); and the scholastic philosopher  Bernard  of Chartres. It was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England. A native Old English form, <i>Beornheard</i>, was superseded by the Norman form."],"variants":[]},{"name":"IV","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Violet  ,   Vivien  , or   Vivian ."],"variants":[{"name":"Vivien","meanings":["Earlier generally taken as a variant of the boy's name   Vivian  , but now also rarely used for boys. This spelling was quite common in Old French. Its use as a girl's name in the English-speaking world was influenced by  Tennyson's  Merlin and Vivien (  1859 ). This name, from Arthurian legend, may represent an altered form of a Celtic name (perhaps akin to the Irish Gaelic name <i>Béibhinn</i> ‘white lady’, pronounced ‘bee-<b>veen</b>’). The actress  Vivien Leigh  (  1913–67 ) was christened <i>Vivian</i>."]},{"name":"Violet","meanings":["From the name of the flower (Old French <i>violette</i>, Late Latin <i>violetta</i>, a diminutive of <i>viola</i>). This was one of the earliest flower names to become popular in Britain, being used as early as  1700  and becoming well established in the 19th century, although it is now somewhat out of favour."]},{"name":"Vivian","meanings":["Originally a boy's name, from an Old French form of the Latin name <i>Vivianus</i> (probably a derivative of <i>vivus</i> ‘alive’), but now more frequent as a girl's name. The name was borne by a 5th-century bishop of Saintes in western France, remembered for protecting his people during the invasion of the Visigoths."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Bernard IV de Melgueil was born in 1091, in Castelnau-le-Lez, Hérault, Occitanie, France, his father, Raymond de Melgueil II, was 23 and his mother, Mrs Marie Melguel, was 27. He married Guillemette de Montpelier on 18 January 1121. They were the parents of at least 2 daughters. He died about 1132, in Le Monastier-sur-Gazeille, Haute-Loire, Auvergne, France, at the age of 42."},"et":{"1091–environ 1132":"1091–umbes 1132","1091–1132":"1091–1132","1087–1149":"1087–1149","1112–1144":"1112–1144","1117–1190":"1117–1190","1068–1120":"1068–1120","1065–Female":"1065–Surnud","1091":"1091","1190":"1190","environ 1132":"umbes 1132","1132":"1132","1120":"1120","18 January 1121":"18. jaanuar 1121","1065":"1065","1087":"1087","1117":"1117","1149":"1149","1068":"1068","1112":"1112","1144":"1144","about 1112":"umbes 1112","Le Monastier-sur-Gazeille, Haute-Loire, Auvergne, France":"Le Monastier-sur-Gazeille, Haute-Loire, Auvergne, Prantsusmaa","France":"Prantsusmaa","Mauguio, Hérault, Occitanie, France":"Mauguio, Hérault, Occitanie, Prantsusmaa","Castelnau-le-Lez, Hérault, Occitanie, France":"Castelnau-le-Lez, Hérault, Occitanie, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1091–environ 1132":"1091–noin 1132","1091–1132":"1091–1132","1087–1149":"1087–1149","1112–1144":"1112–1144","1117–1190":"1117–1190","1068–1120":"1068–1120","1065–Female":"1065–Kuollut","1091":"1091","1190":"1190","environ 1132":"noin 1132","1132":"1132","1120":"1120","18 January 1121":"18. tammikuuta 1121","1065":"1065","1087":"1087","1117":"1117","1149":"1149","1068":"1068","1112":"1112","1144":"1144","about 1112":"noin 1112","Le Monastier-sur-Gazeille, Haute-Loire, Auvergne, France":"Le Monastier-sur-Gazeille, Haute-Loire, Auvergne, Ranska","France":"Ranska","Mauguio, Hérault, Occitanie, France":"Mauguio, Hérault, Occitanie, Ranska","Castelnau-le-Lez, Hérault, Occitanie, France":"Castelnau-le-Lez, Hérault, Occitanie, Ranska"},"fr":{"1091